ul.li: can loosely be seen as the set of all possible values for a
is used to define domains and codomains of functions

div.p: A value a0 of type a is

ul.li: one representative of the set of possible values for the type

g.title: Function that takes parameters or arguments and produces a result

div.h1: an impure function has side effects

ul.li: writes or reads from a file
calls library methods which are not pure (get time, RNG, ...)
... any other expected effect that is not visible in the signature

div.h1: a pure function has NO side effects

ul.li: result depends solely on the arguments
is easy to reason about on use (type semantics)
has an implementation that is easy to check thanks code locality

g.title: Function that takes a domain value of type a and produces a codomain value of type b

div.p: A total function yields values over the whole domain, for any value in a
A partial function is non total, meaning it can break on some values

g.title: Apply function to compute a value of type b (namely b0) from a value of type a (namely a0)
